gomodel:SYNGO_5054  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Automated change 2024-03-14: GO:0099061 replaced by GO:0098839" , "Rationale: Figure 1F: Western blotting of mouse whole-brain lysates showed NSG2 has its greatest expression during the perinatal period and is gradually downregulated thereafter, it continues to be expressed even in adult animals (P60; Fig. 1F).\n\nFigure 1g,h: confocal images of DIV14-DIV16 hippocampal neurons a portion of endogenous NSG2 (29%) and overexpressed NSG2 (37%) co-localized with postsynaptic marker protein Homer1.\n\nFigure 2: confocal images of DIV15 hippocampal neurons showed partial (~40%) co-localization of NSG2 with GluA1 (GRIA1) and GluA2 (GRIA2).\n\nFigure 3c: co-immunoprecipitation showed NSG2 can interact with AMPAR subunits GluA1 and GluA2 in whole-brain lysate of P0 mouse.\n\nBased on the known transmembrane topology of this protein, \"integral component of ... membrane\" term was selected.. Experimental description: Result section, related to confocal imaging in Figure 1: \"Similarly, NSG2 was detected by 4 d in vitro (DIV4) in cultured mouse hippocampal neurons (Fig. 1A)\". Although not explicitly stated, synaptic localization shown in Figure 1G is on same tissue (thus we selected mouse species targeted by antibody against the endogenous protein).\n\n\"Episomal vectors encoding mCherry or NSG2-mCherry (NSG2-mC) were generated in house by cloning either mCherry or the open reading frame of human NSG2 (NM_015980.4) in frame with mCherry into the pCS2+ mammalian expression plasmid (kind gift from Bill Bement, University of Wisconsin).\"\n\nantibody:\nPrimary antibodies consisted of rabbit anti-NSG2 (1:500; Abcam)" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-4973-5732" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" ;
        dc:date           "2024-03-14" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_CC_5054" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

